9. Failure Analysis: When the Ball Hits the Hotdog Machine

When an AI answer is bad, the immediate public response is often:

“The AI is stupid.”

This may be correct.

However, the Institutional Lane Review Board recommends first checking whether the user accidentally requested “something about strategy” with no audience, no evidence, no constraints, no definition of success, and the emotional energy of a man throwing cutlery into a drawer.

9.1 Common Failure Modes

Failure	Likely Cause	Corrective Rail
Too vague	Goal unclear	“Give me three practical options.”
Too long	Format unspecified	“Keep it under 300 words.”
Too technical	Audience missing	“Write for a non-technical reader.”
Too confident	Uncertainty not requested	“Flag assumptions and unknowns.”
Too generic	Context missing	“Use the details below.”
Too weird	Tone groove contaminated	“Use neutral plain English.”
Too salesy	Hype groove activated	“Avoid marketing language.”
Too lawyerly	Risk frame overactivated	“Do not write legal advice; explain practical considerations.”
Made things up	Evidence boundary missing	“Use only provided facts; say when you do not know.”

9.2 Official Finding

Most poor outputs are not mysterious.

They are lane-design incidents.

